{"key":"post-15668885","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15668885</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Jw6457 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;What's a typical time to let wbs dry after simmering and rinsing in colonder one last time. Worried about having the moisture content correct.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You're letting the tail wag the dog.&amp;nbsp; You want the grains totally dry on the outside.&amp;nbsp; The moisture you want is on the inside.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Never rinse after boiling, because this cools off the grains.&amp;nbsp; Rinse the dry grains before you boil, and then when you pour it into the colander, the water will drain, and the surface moisture will steam off.&amp;nbsp; By shaking the colander a few times, you can get more steam to rise off the grains, leaving them dry.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The procedure is demonstrated in full on the &quot;Let's Grow Mushrooms&quot; DVD, a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Grain-Preparation&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;sample clip&lt;/a&gt; of which can be viewed on my site.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>15668879</prev>\n<first>15668643</first>\n<last>15668885</last>\n<when>1326646308</when>\n<utime>01/15/12 06:51 PM</utime>\n</post>"}